TEDTalk Tuesday Ep2: first, I’ll start off by saying that there are so many well meaning people who use this term and this isn’t to shame anyone! I just personally feel like it would be so hurtful to hear someone say that my own child is “low functioning” and/or that they are in the “low functioning” class. Or to know that that is how others think of you. So what do I say instead? I try to be more specific rather than classifying them as a whole- for example, saying “they need constant support for navigating the campus” “they are in a class that has a lot of support staff” “they are still learning how to best communicate”… In general I think our functioning fluctuates around our own baselines. I am low functioning when there is no sun and I can’t find motivation 😫I am high functioning after I work out early and then take a hot shower 🙌🏾 shouldn’t everyone have the right to have a baseline and fluctuate? 🤷🏽‍♀️ Don’t agree with me? That’s chill- tell me your stance, I’m listening 👂🏾

TEDTalk Tuesday Ep: 3! Let’s talk about “Autistic person” Vs. “Person with Autism” A New Perspective! Here’s what I’ve gathered- I was taught by my credential professors to say “person with Autism” which is called person first language. I have since changed my prospective. I follow a lot of Autistic Adult instagram accounts on my personal page and have learned SO MUCH straight from the source. According to many of their accounts, they prefer Autistic because Autism is a part of them and something they are not ashamed of, many proud of. When I thought about it like this it totally makes sense. I wouldn’t be upset or bothered if someone identified me (in a well meaning way) by saying “that Filipino girl” because I enjoy that part of me. 
On the other other hand- I’ve found that parents of autistic children prefer “person/child with autism” when referring to their child. 
All in all- when ever possible and appropriate, just ask! I’m not suggesting asking a random person on the street but if you have a family member or someone else you are close with then you can ask them. I ask my students after they get settled in. 
**One more thing to clarify: using this identifier is when it fits the contexts. I am not saying that it is necessary to announce Autism every time you casually discuss a person. 
I hope I was able to summarize this clearly. I could write about 87 more pages on this subject 🥰💚

💚 Smoothing buttercream onto a cake- round and round and round continuously at about a 30 degree with a lot of the scraper touching the cake. This is about a 30 degree angle. Scraper: @shoptheflourgirl 
💚 Finishing scrapes- about a 75 degree angle. For this, you are basically scraping off a thin layer of buttercream. You want just a tiny bit of the scraper to touch the cake. Triple Colored Macarons! I love me a color swirl!!! Here’s how to do it! 
1- know how to make macarons already 
2- add dry ingredients to the meringue and begin to macaronage until ingredients are distributed evenly! DO NOT MACARONAGE TOO MUCH HERE! 
3- split your batch into 3! You could measure if you wanted but I just eyeballed it here! 
4- add your color. I use gel because I feel like it mixes in better for batter that is already pre-macaronaged 
5- lay your colors down side by side on Saran Wrap and wrap that baby up! 
6- snip off the end and put it into a piping bag. I use a 12 @wiltoncakes tip or @shoptheflourgirl tip 
7- pipe and bake as you would! 💕💚🌈 Happy Baking 🫶🏾

My absolute favorite for any dessert! PASSION FRUIT CURD! 
💚 You can use a purée, fresh or frozen. I find halfed frozen passion fruit at my local Mexican market! Maracuyá
💚You have the option of straining the seeds. I like them and they are also good for you so basically this is a salad!

🧡💛Recipe:
4 yolks + whole egg 
1 cup sugar 
-mix and set aside 
2/3 cup of passion fruit 
1/2 cup room temp butter 
Dash of salt 
-warm on low/medium until butter is melted 
-temper the egg/sugar with warm mixture 
-pour tempered eggs/sugar back in pot 
-put ok the stove and heat to at least 160F. I like to cook it just past that to make it slightly thicker 
-let cool at room temp for several minutes then in the fridge 
-Enjoy the F out of this yummy curd!! 🧡💛

TED Talk Tuesday Ep:7 Do you agree/disagree? Should everyone be pushed to give eye contact even if it is distracting, causing anxiety and even painful? Please note that I mentioned this is referencing people/students who are noticeably struggling with eye contact (not everyone). 
Here is what trying to give eye contact can be like- 
“…it’s the mental equivalent to ear splitting noise” 
“Eye contact can feel painful and abusive” 
“Communication should be about a mutual respect between two people and their boundaries”
“If I was forced to look then they told me I stared, if I didn’t then they told me I was ignorant and I never got it right” 
“We look away so we can concentrate and listen to you” 
The down side is- I know that much of society doesn’t know or understand this. (Thank YOU for reading this and educating yourself!) So do I prep my students for an unknowing society or respect boundaries and let my students be themselves? 🤷🏽‍♀️

Swiss Meringue cookies! Endless possibilities. What makes them Swiss? You heat the egg whites and sugar prior to whipping! I tried with carton egg whites and it did not work out for me personally. Here are the steps:
•100g (or 3 large eggs) egg whites 
•200g (or 1 cup) of sugar 
In a metal bowl over a double boiler. Whisk until at least 130F or dip your finger in and rub to feel that the sugar is dissolved and there are no crystals 
•Use a mixer, start slow and move up to the fastest speed until firm peaks are formed. 
•Add in your desired flavor and a pinch of salt. *I love almond extract with these! 
•Do one more quick mix. 
•Color ONLY WITH GEL OR POWDER! No oil based or they will immediately deflate! This Is Very important! If you are doing all one color then you can add that while mixing. 
•Pipe out to whatever shapes you want. 
•You can use a damp finger tip to pat down any peaks you don’t want 
Bake at 190F for 1-3 hour’s depending on the size and desired textured. After their time is done, turn oven off and leave the meringues in there for another hour. For these 2 inch cookies I baked for 2 hours. 
Done!

*Check out what I’ve done this simple Marshmallow recipe in previous reels! 
3/4 cup powdered sugar 
1/2 cup corn starch 

1 cup cold water 
3- .25 oz gelatin packets 
2/3 light corn syrup 
2 cups sugar 
1/2 tsp salt 
2 tsp vanilla 
.
Combine half of the powdered sugar and corn starch and set aside. 
.
1.Grease a 9x13 pan and set aside. (I am using a smaller pan in the video because I used half the mixture for other projects)
2.In your kitchen aid bowl,  Pour 1/2 cup of water and sprinkle 3 gelatin packets over the water. Do not mix. Let bloom & firm for 10 minutes. 
3.In a saucepan Combine 1/2 cup water, light corn syrup sugar and salt and heat over medium heat. Let boil and reach 240 degrees F. Sugar will be fully dissolved. 
4.Turn your mixer on low with the gelatin mixture in it. Gently pour syrup into the mixer over the bloomed gelatin. Stream the syrup into the middle versus the  of the bowl side. 
5.Whip on high for 8-10 minutes until thick and glossy. 
6.Quickly pour and scrape mixture into prepared 9x13 pan. You need to work quickly. 
7.Dust corn starch and powdered mixture over the top and loosely cover with plastic wrap. 
8.Let sit at room temp over night or at least 8 hours. 
9.Once firm, flip out marshmallows and dust with remaining powdered sugar/corn starch mixture and cut! I like to cut using a bench scraper/cake scraper! 
10.Congrats! You will never look at a store bought marshmallow the same again! 🤣
*If you want a sprinkled side then you need to add the sprinkles right away before the marshmallows firm up!

Chocolate Haupia Pie! Aka Coconut/chocolate deliciousness! 
•
1-Pie crust 
1- 13.5oz can of coconut milk (this is not drinking carton milk!) 
1 cup regular milk 
1 cup of sugar 
1 cup of water 
1/2 cup corn starch
1tsp (ish) of coconut extract
1/2 cup-1 1/4 cup chocolate of choice. The amount of chocolate is preference (I put less chocolate because I like the coconut so much and I also use dark chocolate) 
Toasted coconut for toppings (no one actually measures that) 
*homemade or store bought whip cream 
*When I’m ballin out of control I add toasted macadamia nuts too 😝 
•••
Blind bake the pie crust and let fully cool. combine coconut milk, regular milk and sugar in a pot and bring to a low boil on med/low heat. In the mean time, mix the 1 cup of water and 1/2 cup corn starch in a cup. Once the milks are lightly boiling, pour in corn starch/water slurry and stir constantly. Continue to cook for 2-4 minutes until it thickens. Take it off the heat and add coconut extract. Add chopped chocolate to a separate bowl (I prefer not plastic so it holds the heat). Pour slightly less than half of the coconut mixture into the chocolate bowl. Let sit for a minute to melt then stir to combine. Once the chocolate is fully melted into the coconut mixture, pour chocolate into the pie crust. Gently pour the full coconut mixture over top. Give a jiggle wiggle. Let it firm in the fridge over night or at least 6 hours. Top with whipped cream, toasted coconut and more chocolate or whatever you want because it’s your damn pie! 😘 enjoy and tag me! 💚💚💚
